subject: Add ability to view all the dumps
commitMessage:
Add ability to view all the dumps

The story is integration of these two API responses
for their respective dumps:

1.Resource and Hostboot dumps:
redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/Dump/Entries
2.BMC Dumps: /redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/LogServices/Dump/Entries

Signed-off-by: Sukanya Pandey <sukapan1@in.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I24ded733e682d21904e92e2e8be1951e46d33b09

You can still follow the odata.id for LogServices and Entries.
Just an observation, but I found myself a little confused as to why there was a getBMCDumps and getAllDumps without a getSystemDumps. It might be nice to have a getSystemDumps as well.
I like the comments, but I feel the two you are using for system and bmc dumps adequately inform the user that there are the sections for dump initiation without this one. 😊

There could be other types of dumps in the future. Can we name this after the service to make it generic, something like:

getSystemDumpEnteries

and we could follow that same naming convention for BMC dumps also, e.g. getBmcDumpEntries
This assumes that the Managers list is of size 1, which the redfish spec does not gaurantee.  This also implies that the collection has an order, which the spec doesn't gaurantee.

I agree, so as its not certain which index will hold correct API value, i have used template literals to make the code less hardcoded, something like api.get(`${response.data['@odata.id']}/bmc`)

Where {response.data['@odata.id']} will be coming from spec and as 'bmc' is required at the end of the API, I have concatenated that.

This is still hardcoding the name "bmc" which the spec doesn't allow.  Please don't do that.
Same here.  There's no guarantee there is only one system, and in fact, I believe this API has 2 members, so this is hardcoding an assumption that the redfish spec does not promise.

The redfish spec does not guarantee this ID exists, or remains the same between versions.  Please do not hardcode it.

If it helps, I'm happy to obfuscate these IDs on the bmcweb side now such that they meet the Redfish spec, but can no longer be relied on.  That will need to be done when we implement caching anyway, so best to do it now?

We are going to move forward with this change with the intent to remove the hardcoded paths in a separate commit. 

Here is the hardcode fix proposal we are discussing Wednesday https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/webui-vue/+/47141

I'm not quite understanding why we're merging something that we know is incorrect, and actively pushes us further away from the goal of being able to cache the Redfish endpoints, as well as makes us incompatible with all other redfish implementations.  If we're going to merge this, what is the expected timeline on fixing it and who will take ownership to fix it?
